the practices through which advertising understood and represented the ‘modern housewife’ and domestic consumption were influenced by American advertising and commercial culture. In doing so, he challenges the way critics and historians have often understood Anglo-American relations, and shows how American influences across a range of areas of advertising practice were not only a source of inspiration, but were also adapted and reworked to speak more effectively to the British consumer.Hard sell offers a major new analysis of the techniques of advertising in the decades of post-war affluence and advertising’s relationship to the social changes associated with growing prosperity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdvertisingxSocial aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aAdvertisingzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aAmericanization.  aAnglo-American relations.  aBritish advertising.  aJ Walter Thompson.  aJWT London.  aTV commercials.  aaffluence.  acultural critics.  adocumentary film.  ahard sell advertising.  amarket research.  amass consumption.  amass housewife.  atelevision advertising.  atrans-Atlantic relations.1 aNixon, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611117340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526111173423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526111173/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles